Desert]]\n[[Category:University towns in the United States]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1775]]\n[[Category:1775 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:1775 establishments in New Spain]]\n[[Category:Butterfield Overland Mail]]\n[[Category:San Antonio-San Diego Mail Line]]\n[[Category:Stagecoach stops in the United States]]\n[[Category:Cities in Pima County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "70.162.50.153", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Facts)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tucson,_Arizona"}
{"title_page": "Chickasha Chiefs", "text_new": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Chickasha Chiefs\n|allyears         = 1904\u20131952   \n|city             = Chickasha, Oklahoma\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level =  Class D (1904, 1920\u20131922, 1948\u20131952)\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Southwestern League]] (1904)\n*[[Western Association]] (1920\u20131921)\n*[[Oklahoma State League]] (1922)\n*[[Sooner State League]] (1948\u20131952)\n}}\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = None\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        =  {{plainlist|\n*Chickasha Indians(1904)\n*Chickasha Chicks (1920\u20131922)\n*'''Chickasha Chiefs''' (1948\u20131952)\n}}\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        = {{plainlist|\n*Borden Park (1948\u20131952)\n*University Park (1920-1922)\n}}\n|leaguechamps     = 1920, 1921\n|divisionchamps   = \n|owner            = \n|manager          = \n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Chickasha Chiefs''' was the primary name of the  [[minor league baseball]] team based in [[Chickasha, Oklahoma]] between 1904\u20131952. The Chickasha Chiefs were a member of the Class D [[Sooner State League]] (1948\u20131952). Chickasha also hosted teams in the [[Southwestern League]] (1904), [[Western Association]] (1920\u20131921) and [[Oklahoma State League]] (1922).\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Chickasha when Chickasha briefly had a team in 1904. The Shawnee Browns of the [[Southwestern League]] moved to Chickasha, Oklahoma on June 30, 1904. The team became the '''Chickasha Indians''' and continued play in the Southwestern League. However, the franchise returned to [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]] on August 3, 1904. The franchise then disbanded on September 5, 1904.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Shawnee_Browns |title=Shawnee Browns - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Chickasha_Indians |title=Chickasha Indians - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-sb14527|title=Shawnee/Chickasha Indians/Shawnee Browns Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nBaseball returned in 1920, when the '''Chickasha Chicks''' began play in the eight-team [[Western Association]]. The Western Association had just reformed after a two-year hiatus. Other 1920 league members were the Drumright Drummers, Enid Harvesters, [[Fort Smith Twins]], Henryetta Hens, [[Okmulgee Drillers]], [[Pawhuska Huskers]] and Springfield Merchants.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-WA/y-1920|title=1920 Western Association (WA) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Western_Association |title=Western Association - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn their first full season of play, the Chickasha Chicks finished 52\u201372 (7th) in the 1920 Western Association.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe Chickasha Chicks won the 1921 Western Association Championship. The Chicks finished 74\u201374 (5th overall) in the regular season and captured the first-half pennant. In the playoff Finals, the Chickasha Chicks defeated the [[Fort Smith Twins]] 4 games to 3 to claim the 1921 championship.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-WA/y-1921|title=1921 Western Association (WA) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10868/y-1921|title=1921 Chickasha Chicks Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nChickasha left the Western Association to join the newly formed [[Oklahoma State League]] in 1922 and won their second straight championship. Other charter members of the six-team 1922 Oklahoma State League were the Clinton Bulldogs, Duncan Oilers, El Reno Railroaders, [[Guthrie, Oklahoma]] and Wilson Drillers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-OKSL2/y-1922|title=1922 Oklahoma State League (OSL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Oklahoma_State_League |title=Oklahoma State League - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date=2016-12-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nPlaying in the new league in 1922, the Chickasha Chicks finished 55\u201355 (3rd) in the regular season. In the playoff Finals, the Chickasha Chicks defeated the Clinton Bulldogs 4 games 0 to claim the 1922 championship. However, Chickasha was relegated to playing on the road in the second half of the season. After the 1922 championship season the franchise folded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10868/y-1922|title=1922 Chickasha Chicks Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 1948, the Chickasha Chiefs began play in the [[Sooner State League]]. The Chiefs and [[Ada Herefords]] were expansion teams in the league as it expanded from six-teams to eight-teams after forming in 1947. The other 1948 Sooner State League members were the Ada Herefords, [[Ardmore Indians]], [[Duncan Cementers]], [[Lawton Giants]], [[McAlester Rockets]], [[Pauls Valley Raiders]] and [[Seminole Oilers]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1948|title=1948 Sooner State League (SSL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Sooner_State_League |title=Sooner State League - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nChickasha qualified for the playoffs in 1948. The Chicks finished 73\u201363 (4th) in the regular season. In the playoffs, the McAlester Rockets defeated the Chickasha Chiefs 3 games to 1. The Chiefs 1948 attendance was 35,640, an average of 524 per game.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1948|title=1948 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nReturning to the playoffs in 1949, the Chickasha Chicks finished 78\u201361 (3rd) in the regular season. In the 1949 playoffs, the Lawton Giants defeated Chickasha 3 games to 0. The Chicks 1949 attendance was 59,306, an average of 853.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1949|title=1949 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1950 Chickasha Chiefs finished 80\u201359 (3rd) in the Sooner State League regular season. Qualifying for the playoffs, the McAlester Rockets defeated the Chiefs 3 games to 0. The 1950 season attendance was 43,759 (3rd in the league).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1950|title=1950 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nIn 1951, the Chickasha Chiefs used five managers in finishing 46\u201394 (7th) in the Sooner State League. The 1951 season attendance was 21,107.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1951|title=1951 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe Chickasha Chiefs returned to the Sooner State League playoffs in 1952. The Chiefs finished 78\u201362 (3rd) in the 1952 regular season. In the playoffs, the Pauls Valley Raiders defeated the Chickasha Chiefs 3 games to 1. Season attendance: 27,494, an average of 393.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1952|title=1952 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nthe Chickasha Chiefs folded after the 1952 season and were replaced by the [[Gainesville Owls]] in the 1953 Sooner State League. Chickasha hasn't hosted another minor league baseball team.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n==The ballparks==\nThe Chickasha Chiefs played at '''Memorial Park''', also referred to as '''Borden Park'''. Borden Park burned in August 1950 and was rebuilt for the following season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/OKPCP/browse/?fq=str_year%3A1950&fq=str_month%3A08_aug&fq=str_day%3A14&fq=str_location_county%3AGrady+County%2C+OK|title=Photograph Taken at Night of Crowd Standing Near Charred Ruins|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3ASapulpa+Daily+Herald&fq=str_year%3A1950&fq=str_month%3A11_nov&fq=str_day%3A13|title=Sports Briefs, Sapulpa Daily Herald, Nov. 13, 1950, p.3|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref> The ballpark had a capacity of 1,700 (1950) and 2,500 (1952). Borden Park, which is now called Elliott Field and is used for high school baseball, was located at 200 North 19th Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyclopedia.sabr.org/wiki/Borden_Park|title=Borden Park|website=encyclopedia.sabr.org}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1920 through 1922, the Chickasha Chicks played at '''University Park'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3AThe+Chickasha+Daily+Express&fq=str_year%3A1920&fq=str_month%3A04_apr&fq=str_day%3A21|title=Fans Ready For Big Clash With Enid Team Here, Chickasha Daily Express, Apr. 21, 1920, p.1|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref> University Park, which had previously hosted exhibition games featuring Hall of Fame pitcher [[Walter Johnson]], was located at the terminus of the street railway line near present-day Shannon Springs Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnwpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA239&lpg=PA239&dq=chickasha+%22street+railway%22+%22university+park%22&source=bl&ots=qNaCCgqlDn&sig=ACfU3U0xiC-Si9cFn5h0aabY37Dz6l6Oig&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHwOfTv4TpAhWwlHIEHZlpC3wQ6AEwCnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=chickasha%20%22street%20railway%22%20%22university%20park%22&f=false|title=McGraw Electric Railway Manual (1910), p.239|website=books.google.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/feed/227607/grady-county-historical-society-museum|title=Grady County Historical Society Museum, Daily Oklahoman, Dec. 10, 2010|website=oklahoman.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3AThe+Chickasha+Daily+Express&fq=str_year%3A1914&fq=str_month%3A10_oct&fq=str_day%3A26|title=Getting Near Glimpse of Premier Pitcher, Chickasha Daily Express, Oct. 26, 1914, p.1|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Ed Cole (baseball)|Ed Cole]] (1950)\n*[[Mike Cvengros]] (1921)\n*[[Camilo Pascual]] (1951) [[Minnesota Twins Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Ned Pettigrew]] (1920, MGR)\n*[[Pete Runnels]] (1949) 5\u00d7 MLB All-Star, 2\u00d7 AL batting champion (1960, 1962), [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Guy Sturdy]] (1921)\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External references==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Chickasha,_OK Baseball Reference]\n\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Grady County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Minor League Baseball\n|name             = Chickasha Chiefs\n|allyears         = 1904\u20131952   \n|city             = Chickasha, Oklahoma\n|misc             =\n|logo             = \n|uniformlogo      = \n|class level      =  \n|past class level =  Class D (1904, 1920\u20131922, 1948\u20131952)\n|current league   = \n|conference       =\n|division         = \n|past league      = {{plainlist|\n*[[Southwestern League]] (1904)\n*[[Western Association]] (1920\u20131921)\n*[[Oklahoma State League]] (1922)\n*[[Sooner State League]] (1948\u20131952)\n}}\n|majorleague      = \n|pastmajorleague  = None\n|nickname         = \n|pastnames        =  {{plainlist|\n*Chickasha Indians(1904)\n*Chickasha Chicks (1920\u20131922)\n*'''Chickasha Chiefs''' (1948\u20131952)\n}}\n|ballpark         = \n|pastparks        = {{plainlist|\n*Borden Park (1948\u20131952)\n*University Park (1920-1922)\n}}\n|leaguechamps     = 1920, 1921\n|divisionchamps   = \n|owner            = \n|manager          = \n|gm               =\n}}\nThe '''Chickasha Chiefs''' was the primary name of the  [[minor league baseball]] team based in [[Chickasha, Oklahoma]] between 1904\u20131952. The Chickasha Chiefs were a member of the Class D [[Sooner State League]] (1948\u20131952). Chickasha also hosted teams in the [[Southwestern League]] (1904), [[Western Association]] (1920\u20131921) and [[Oklahoma State League]] (1922).\n\n==History==\nMinor league baseball began in Chickasha when Chickasha briefly had a team in 1904. The Shawnee Browns of the [[Southwestern League]] moved to Chickasha, Oklahoma on June 30, 1904. The team became the '''Chickasha Indians''' and continued play in the Southwestern League. However, the franchise returned to [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]] on August 3, 1904. The franchise then disbanded on September 5, 1904.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Shawnee_Browns |title=Shawnee Browns - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Chickasha_Indians |title=Chickasha Indians - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/t-sb14527|title=Shawnee/Chickasha Indians/Shawnee Browns Statistics and Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nBaseball returned in 1920, when the '''Chickasha Chicks''' began play in the eight-team [[Western Association]]. The Western Association had just reformed after a two-year hiatus. Other 1920 league members were the Drumright Drummers, Enid Harvesters, [[Fort Smith Twins]], Henryetta Hens, [[Okmulgee Drillers]], [[Pawhuska Huskers]] and Springfield Merchants.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-WA/y-1920|title=1920 Western Association (WA) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Western_Association |title=Western Association - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn their first full season of play, the Chickasha Chicks finished 52\u201372 (7th) in the 1920 Western Association.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n\nThe Chickasha Chicks won the 1921 Western Association Championship. The Chicks finished 74\u201374 (5th overall) in the regular season and captured the first-half pennant. In the playoff Finals, the Chickasha Chicks defeated the [[Fort Smith Twins]] 4 games to 3 to claim the 1921 championship.<ref name=autogenerated5 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-WA/y-1921|title=1921 Western Association (WA) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10868/y-1921|title=1921 Chickasha Chicks Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nChickasha left the Western Association to join the newly formed [[Oklahoma State League]] in 1922 and won their second straight championship. Other charter members of the six-team 1922 Oklahoma State League were the Clinton Bulldogs, Duncan Oilers, El Reno Railroaders, [[Guthrie, Oklahoma]] and Wilson Drillers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-OKSL2/y-1922|title=1922 Oklahoma State League (OSL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Oklahoma_State_League |title=Oklahoma State League - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date=2016-12-29 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nPlaying in the new league in 1922, the Chickasha Chicks finished 55\u201355 (3rd) in the regular season. In the playoff Finals, the Chickasha Chicks defeated the Clinton Bulldogs 4 games 0 to claim the 1922 championship. However, Chickasha was relegated to playing on the road in the second half of the season. After the 1922 championship season the franchise folded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10868/y-1922|title=1922 Chickasha Chicks Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated6 />\n\nIn 1948, the Chickasha Chiefs began play in the [[Sooner State League]]. The Chiefs and [[Ada Herefords]] were expansion teams in the league as it expanded from six-teams to eight-teams after forming in 1947. The other 1948 Sooner State League members were the Ada Herefords, [[Ardmore Indians]], [[Duncan Cementers]], [[Lawton Giants]], [[McAlester Rockets]], [[Pauls Valley Raiders]] and [[Seminole Oilers]].<ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/l-SOSL/y-1948|title=1948 Sooner State League (SSL) on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Sooner_State_League |title=Sooner State League - BR Bullpen |publisher=Baseball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nChickasha qualified for the playoffs in 1948. The Chicks finished 73\u201363 (4th) in the regular season. In the playoffs, the McAlester Rockets defeated the Chickasha Chiefs 3 games to 1. The Chiefs 1948 attendance was 35,640, an average of 524 per game.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1948|title=1948 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nReturning to the playoffs in 1949, the Chickasha Chicks finished 78\u201361 (3rd) in the regular season. In the 1949 playoffs, the Lawton Giants defeated Chickasha 3 games to 0. The Chicks 1949 attendance was 59,306, an average of 853.<ref name=autogenerated4 /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1949|title=1949 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe 1950 Chickasha Chiefs finished 80\u201359 (3rd) in the Sooner State League regular season. Qualifying for the playoffs, the McAlester Rockets defeated the Chiefs 3 games to 0. The 1950 season attendance was 43,759 (3rd in the league).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1950|title=1950 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nIn 1951, the Chickasha Chiefs used five managers in finishing 46\u201394 (7th) in the Sooner State League. The 1951 season attendance was 21,107.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1951|title=1951 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated3 />\n\nThe Chickasha Chiefs returned to the Sooner State League playoffs in 1952. The Chiefs finished 78\u201362 (3rd) in the 1952 regular season. In the playoffs, the Pauls Valley Raiders defeated the Chickasha Chiefs 3 games to 1. Season attendance: 27,494, an average of 393.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.statscrew.com/minorbaseball/roster/t-cc10869/y-1952|title=1952 Chickasha Chiefs Roster on StatsCrew.com|website=www.statscrew.com}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\nthe Chickasha Chiefs folded after the 1952 season and were replaced by the [[Gainesville Owls]] in the 1953 Sooner State League. Chickasha hasn't hosted another minor league baseball team.<ref name=autogenerated4 />\n\n==The ballpark==\nThe Chickasha Chiefs played at '''Memorial Park''', also referred to as '''Borden Park'''. Borden Park burned in August 1950 and was rebuilt for the following season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/OKPCP/browse/?fq=str_year%3A1950&fq=str_month%3A08_aug&fq=str_day%3A14&fq=str_location_county%3AGrady+County%2C+OK|title=Photograph Taken at Night of Crowd Standing Near Charred Ruins|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3ASapulpa+Daily+Herald&fq=str_year%3A1950&fq=str_month%3A11_nov&fq=str_day%3A13|title=Sports Briefs, Sapulpa Daily Herald, Nov. 13, 1950, p.3|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref> The ballpark had a capacity of 1,700 (1950) and 2,500 (1952). Borden Park, which is now called Elliott Field and is used for high school baseball, was located at 200 North 19th Street.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://encyclopedia.sabr.org/wiki/Borden_Park|title=Borden Park|website=encyclopedia.sabr.org}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1920 through 1922, the Chickasha Chicks played at '''University Park'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3AThe+Chickasha+Daily+Express&fq=str_year%3A1920&fq=str_month%3A04_apr&fq=str_day%3A21|title=Fans Ready For Big Clash With Enid Team Here, Chickasha Daily Express, Apr. 21, 1920, p.1|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref> University Park, which had previously hosted exhibition games featuring Hall of Fame pitcher [[Walter Johnson]], was located at the terminus of the street railway line near present-day Shannon Springs Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BnwpAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA239&lpg=PA239&dq=chickasha+%22street+railway%22+%22university+park%22&source=bl&ots=qNaCCgqlDn&sig=ACfU3U0xiC-Si9cFn5h0aabY37Dz6l6Oig&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiHwOfTv4TpAhWwlHIEHZlpC3wQ6AEwCnoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=chickasha%20%22street%20railway%22%20%22university%20park%22&f=false|title=McGraw Electric Railway Manual (1910), p.239|website=books.google.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://oklahoman.com/article/feed/227607/grady-county-historical-society-museum|title=Grady County Historical Society Museum, Daily Oklahoman, Dec. 10, 2010|website=oklahoman.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gateway.okhistory.org/explore/collections/odnp/browse/?fq=str_title_serial%3AThe+Chickasha+Daily+Express&fq=str_year%3A1914&fq=str_month%3A10_oct&fq=str_day%3A26|title=Getting Near Glimpse of Premier Pitcher, Chickasha Daily Express, Oct. 26, 1914, p.1|website=gateway.okhistory.org}}</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n*[[Ed Cole (baseball)|Ed Cole]] (1950)\n*[[Mike Cvengros]] (1921)\n*[[Camilo Pascual]] (1951) [[Minnesota Twins Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Ned Pettigrew]] (1920, MGR)\n*[[Pete Runnels]] (1949) 5\u00d7 MLB All-Star, 2\u00d7 AL batting champion (1960, 1962), [[Boston Red Sox Hall of Fame]]\n*[[Guy Sturdy]] (1921)\n\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External references==\n[https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Chickasha,_OK Baseball Reference]\n\n[[Category:Minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Defunct minor league baseball teams]]\n[[Category:Sports teams in Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Grady County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Defunct baseball teams in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Skilgis1900", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe ballpark", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chickasha_Chiefs"}
